result.execSummary:
The defendant Domonick A Tranetzki was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Trespass to Dwelling [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14.
  • Criminal Damage to Property [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
The defendant must maintain/obtain full time employment/school that consists of at least 35 hrs/week.

When not full time employed/school, the defendant must apply for at least 3 jobs per week and report progress monthly to P&P with pertinent information in regards to applications.  The defendant must only apply for jobs qualified for - must accept any job offered - must not engage in any conduct that could result in the termination of his/her employment/school.

No consumption or possession of alcohol and no entry into any taverns or bars. 

No contact with victim Harvey Frank.
The defendant is eligible for expunction under 973.015 upon successful completion of probation and has accomplished all conditions of probation.
The defendant must submit a DNA sample.
The defendant must undergo an AODA assessment and follow thru with all recommendations.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Domonick A Tranetzki in court with attorney Chad Lynch.  Defendant Domonick A Tranetzki in custody.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called 2:41 PM. State here for SEHR. Lynch has received copy of revocation packet, no inaccuracies. State some confusion on days of credit. Lynch believes 189 days of credit 16CF217, 200 days of credit on 15CF164, so 11 days. Court reviews credit issue. State is asking for one of two sentences - either 18 months in FC jail on each count, consecutive to each other but concurrent to existing sentence he is currently serving or sentence to 9 months in FC jail on each count, concurrent to each other but consecutive to existing sentence he is currently serving. Lynch makes statement and asks for 60 days in FC jail, concurrent to each other but consecutive to current sentence. Tranetzki makes statement, remorseful. Court accepts statements of all parties and sentences to the following: Counts 1 & 2 - imposes 90 days in FC jail on each count, concurrent to each other but consecutive to the sentence he is currently serving on 16CF217, credit of 12 days, jail time is with huber, good time and community service. Enter civil judgment for any unpaid fines, appeal rights given.
Sentencing hearing on revocation on March 1, 2018 at 02:45 pm.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Domonick A Tranetzki in court with attorney Mary L. Roth Burns.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 9:19 AM. State - resolved - have complied with victim notification requirements with no response or VIS - count #1 - amend to criminal trespass to a dwelling contrary 943.14 - read new charge and penalty - plead to count #2 as alleged both as PTAC, withhold sentence on each county and place on probation for 18 months with conditions of: $300.00 fine plus costs on count #1, count #2 - court costs only, AODA with follow thru, absolute sobriety, no possession of alcohol and no entry into any taverns or bars or similar class B establishments, employment/school, 100 hours of community service, no contact with victim Harvey Frank. Tranetzki and Burns agree. Court amends count #1 to criminal trespass to dwelling contrary to 943.14 - read new charge and penalty, PTAC continues on both counts. Tranetzki pleads NC to counts #1 as amended and #2 as alleged. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thry it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his constitutional rights by entering his plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation. Burns makes final argument prior to sentencing - follow joint recommendation - asks for expunction. Tranetzki makes statement. Court sentences the defendant to the following: counts #1 and #2 - withhold sentence and place on probation for 18 months - concurrent to each other - with conditions of: count #1 - $300.00 fine plus costs and surcharges, count #2 - court costs, AODA with follow thru, no possession or consumption of alcohol and no entry into any bars or taverns, maintain/obtain full time employment/school, 100 hours of community service total, no contact with Harvey Frank, submit DNA sample with expunction rights, eligible for expunction under 973.015 upon successful completion of probation and has accomplished all conditions of probation, credit for 1 day only if revoked, right to appeal, adjourned.

Defendant Domonick A Tranetzki in court with attorney Mary L. Roth Burns.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 1:04 PM. State believes the PH is being waived and has filed an Information that mirrors the complaint. Burns and Tranetzki agree. Court has waiver of PH form, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his right to PH, finds probable cause, binds over for trial. Burns has Information that mirrors the complaint, waives reading of it, will proceed to sentencing. Burns enters NG pleas to all counts. Court accepts pleas, continues bond, sets for FPT.  Final pre-trial scheduled for March 9, 2016 at 09:00 am.
